4. **User Experience**:  
   - Jokes should be visible on the page, not in an alert.
   - The same joke should not be shown twice in a row (optional, but improves UX).
   - The page should be accessible and responsive.

---

## **Design Considerations**

- **HTML Structure**:  
  - A heading, a joke display area, and a button.
- **JavaScript Logic**:  
  - Store jokes in an array.
  - On button click, pick a random index.
  - Optionally, avoid repeating the last joke.
- **Accessibility**:  
  - Use semantic HTML.
  - Ensure the button is focusable and labeled.

---

## **Implementation**

Here’s a simple, well-structured HTML file that meets the requirements:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>Random Joke Generator</title>
  <style>
    body {
      font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
      background: #f9f9f9;
      display: flex;
      flex-direction: column;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: center;
      height: 100vh;
      margin: 0;
    }
    .joke-box {
      background: #fff;
      padding: 2em;
      border-radius: 8px;
      box-shadow: 0 2px 8px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);
      margin-bottom: 1em;
      min-width: 300px;
      min-height: 60px;
      display: flex;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: center;
      text-align: center;
      font-size: 1.2em;
    }
    button {
      padding: 0.7em 1.5em;
      font-size: 1em;
      border: none;
      border-radius: 5px;
      background: #007bff;
      color: #fff;
      cursor: pointer;
      transition: background 0.2s;
    }
    button:hover {
      background: #0056b3;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Random Joke Generator</h1>
  <div class="joke-box" id="jokeBox">
    Click the button to see a joke!
  </div>
  <button id="jokeBtn" aria-label="Show a random joke">Show Joke</button>

  <script>
    const jokes = [
      "Why don't scientists trust atoms? Because they make up everything!",
      "Why did the scarecrow win an award? Because he was outstanding in his field!",
      "Why don't programmers like nature? It has too many bugs.",
      "Why did the math book look sad? Because it had too many problems."
    ];

    let lastJokeIndex = -1;

    document.getElementById('jokeBtn').addEventListener('click', function() {
      let index;
      do {
        index = Math.floor(Math.random() * jokes.length);
      } while (index === lastJokeIndex && jokes.length > 1);
      lastJokeIndex = index;
      document.getElementById('jokeBox').textContent = jokes[index];
    });
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

---

## **Explanation**

- **HTML**:  
  - `<h1>` for the title.
  - `<div class="joke-box" id="jokeBox">` for displaying the joke.
  - `<button id="jokeBtn">` for user interaction.
- **CSS**:  
  - Simple styling for readability and aesthetics.
- **JavaScript**:  
  - Stores jokes in an array.
  - On button click, selects a random joke (not repeating the last one).
  - Updates the joke display area.

---

## **Further Enhancements (Optional)**

- Add more jokes.
- Animate the joke display.
- Fetch jokes from an API.
- Allow users to submit their own jokes.

